shortDescription.en-US: This vase was the first piece offered when Rookwood returned to Cincinnati in 2006.

loadingPreamble.en-US: Another artist has already removed this piece from its mold and coated the inside with glaze. Get ready to decorate.

shortDescription.en-US: If you’re a Cincinnatian, you may have seen this tile as part of a backsplash or fireplace surround, or framed in someone’s house.

loadingPreamble.en-US: Another artist has already pressed this tile and sprayed on a background-color glaze. You’re ready to decorate.

homeSubhead.en-US: Can you recreate an iconic Rookwood piece?

selectionPrompt.en-US: Choose an object to learn more about it and start glazing.

en-US: At Rookwood, each piece passes through 16 hands or more before it’s done.
The intense heat of the kiln makes the clay non-porous and gives the glaze a glass-like finish.
If your clay isn’t completely dry going in, the resulting steam might make your piece explode.
If your clay and glaze expand and contract at different rates, the glaze will crackle.
If glaze touches anything else — another pot or the kiln shelf — it will stick.
It’s always a bit of a surprise when you open the kiln!

resultsSubhead.en-US: Did it turn out the way you expected it to?   Try some other options and see what you get next.

shortDescription.en-US: The original Rookwood logo, from 1886, featured just the reversed “R” and “P.” Until 1900, a new flame was added each year. After 1900, Roman numerals under the logo marked the year.
